{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475039"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12483"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12483"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.57,0.02,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4990"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35479"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1846"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9329"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13968"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41 week gestation (post-term) neonate is delivered with noticeable meconium-stained amniotic fluid. The mother had a history of Group B Streptococcus (GBS) colonisation during her previous pregnancy. She was not tested for GBS during the current pregnancy. No antibiotic prophylaxis was given. Upon delivery, the neonate shows significant signs of respiratory distress, including grunting, and nasal flaring. A chest X-ray reveals diffuse bilateral infiltrates and patchy atelectasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administration of intravenous antibiotics","Continuous pulse oximetry and supplemental oxygen administration","Initiation of immediate GBS prophylaxis in the mother","Administration of surfactant","Needle aspiration for suspected pneumothorax"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis neonate likely has meconium aspiration syndrome (MAS). \u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous pulse oximetry and supplemental oxygen administration\u003C/strong\u003E are crucial components of supportive care and this forms the initial step in the management of MAS. It helps in maintaining oxygen saturation levels and in monitoring the neonate\u0027s clinical status closely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would likely need to be commenced given clinical illness in a neonate; however, the primary concern in this case is the diagnosis of MAS and the initial focus must be on the administration of oxygen. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdministration of surfactant\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in severe cases of MAS, but the initial management typically involves supplemental oxygen and monitoring with pulse oximetry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E could cause similar symptoms, the presence of meconium-stained fluid and chest X-ray findings make MAS a more likely diagnosis. Pneumothorax management would be considered if there were other clinical features suggestive of pneumothorax, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst\u003Cstrong\u003E initiation of GBS prophylaxis in the mother \u003C/strong\u003Emust be considered, this is not the priority in the management of the current situation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Continuous pulse oximetry and supplemental oxygen administration are crucial components of supportive care, and this forms the initial step in the management of MAS."],"references":["American Academy of Pediatrics, Committee on Fetus and Newborn. (2014). Meconium-stained amniotic fluid and meconium aspiration syndrome. Pediatrics, 134(6), e1744-e1749. DOI: 10.1542/peds.2014-2956"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35479"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12483"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35479"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-08T17:09:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-08T17:23:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4990"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50206"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":nul